    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-03-24T23:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-03-24T23:00:00-05:00" n="632"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d632">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 Pacific War/2220a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-03-25T00:00:00-04:00"
                            >March 25, 1942—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>218. A United Press report under Chungking date line March 23, published in the
                        <hi rend="italic">Washington Post</hi> and other newspapers, stated <hi
                        rend="italic">inter alia</hi> that <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“President Sun Fo of the legislative department of the Chinese Government
                            today urged President Roosevelt and Prime Minister Churchill to announce
                            a ‘Pacific charter’ which would pledge the United Nations to recognize
                            the independence of India, French Indo-China, Korea and the
                            Philippines.</p>
                        <p>It was the first authoritative expression by a member of the Chungking
                            government on this country’s attitude toward the disputed question of
                            independence of India.<note n="1" xml:id="d632fn1">Generalissimo Chiang
                                Kai-shek, President of the Chinese Executive Yuan (Premier), paid a
                                visit to India in February.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Sun’s views were released in a signed article in the official <hi
                                rend="italic">Central Daily News</hi> and urged that the Chinese
                            government immediately recognize members of a ‘Korean provisional
                            government’”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Department will appreciate receiving any pertinent information you may have or
                    any comments you may wish to make in regard to this report.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
